binding.p: Early modern binding. Tan leather over wooden boards. 4 raised bands and endbands. , stamped in gold: A 142; remnants of paper label.
binding.decoNote: Blind tooled double-line borders and frames forming three rectangular panels; posterior panel blind tooled in a lozenge pattern, centre panel undecorated, and anterior panel plain with a blind tooled double line creating a triangle shape in each outer corner.
binding.condition: Leather slightly stained and worn. Some quires detached from modern spine, revealing binding.

history.origin: Origin and early provenance unknown. The late Carolingian features of the script suggest an approximate date of the 12th century, first half. France? suggested by a former librarian as the origin based on the manuscript's similarity to Stockholm, National Library, MS A 141.
history.provenance: The manuscript has been kept at the National Library since before the 1697 fire, at least. It is listed in Jache's catalogue of 1698 (U 122) as 226, its post-fire signum, which is found also on .

note.p: The first part of the text of the Psalter is missing; it begins in the middle of Psalm 16:5.
Between and two leaves have been torn out resulting in loss of text; the glossed text of the Psalter thus ends in the middle of Psalm 145:4.

Enclosed within the covers is a photocopy of one of the leaves which is missing from the manuscript; it bears the text and gloss of Psalm 9:7–18 (). The leaf was found in in the National Library of Copenhagen by former librarian Oscar Wieselgren, as described in his note on .

supportDesc.condition: The manuscript shows clear signs of use, with dirt around the lower corners and edges. Some holes and tears, some with remnants of stitching (e.g. ); spillage stains at . At the bottom of , the ruling has cut through the parchment.

note.p:
The manuscipt has the traditional layout of an early 12th century glossed book of the Bible (see De Hamel
), with a central column for the Bible text (60 mm), and two surrounding columns for the glosses (outer column 45-50 mm; inner column 35-45 mm). , blind ruling of central column, 18 lines per column, pricking intermittently visible; 16 lines per central column. From and the ruling extends to the spaces intended for the gloss, i.e. the inner and outer columns - and in some cases also the upper margin (e.g. ) as well as a few lines below the bottom line of the central column - at a height of three lines of commentary for each line of Bible text. From , ruling of the spaces intended for the gloss is intermittent.

handDesc.p: Bible text in Late Carolingian minuscule and/or pregothic. Gloss in at least two different Late Carolingian or pregothic hands (e.g. , ).
handDesc.handNote: Late Carolingian minuscule or pregothic (possibly same as Hand 5).

p.note: Top left corner in brown ink: CXXI; below, in pencil: Ps. 16, 4; bottom centre, in Jache's hand in brown ink: 226 Nov. Num, found again on . Mid outer margin, in pencil by an early modern hand: Ps. 17.. , psalm numbers according to the Hebrew numbering in light brown ink by a medieval hand. At Psalm 118, the sections headed by the Hebrew letters Beth and Gimel are numbered as xx and xxi; after this, this numbering ceases.
